WEBVTT

00:02.220 --> 00:07.900
It's 14, Valentine's Day, sitting in the basement 
of the Weissenbaker building, getting ready to

00:08.040 --> 00:13.540
interview Charlie Holland, who got here a little 
more than 50 years ago. Charlie, test your mic.

00:15.640 --> 00:16.848
Testing one, two. Is it all right? Charlie, for 
someone who may not have known you in a few years to

00:18.720 --> 00:25.590
come when they're looking at this material or 
listening to it, would you begin by summarizing

00:29.030 --> 00:33.150
your background and experience, where you grew 
up, went to school, your experience before you got

00:33.130 --> 00:37.990
to Texas A&M? Well, I grew up in western North 
Carolina, and my dad was a Baptist minister. In

00:46.810 --> 00:53.650
fact, I started the first grade the year he 
finished Wake Forest. He had been in World War I,

00:54.210 --> 00:58.230
and he decided to go down and finish up. So we moved 
to Wake Forest, and about Christmas time, My twins

01:03.410 --> 01:06.650
were born, and he took me out of the first grade 
because he was afraid I might bring home some

01:06.630 --> 01:10.530
childhood diseases. And then the next year after 
that, we moved to Mountain View, and I was just

01:19.190 --> 01:23.290
recently at Christmas going up there looking for 
the place that we moved to. It was on a dirt road out

01:23.830 --> 01:26.490
from North Wilkesboro. And this will kind of give 
you the view of what things were like in those

01:27.410 --> 01:31.950
times. And he was pastor of a little Baptist church 
there, and it was a Baptist junior college high

01:36.780 --> 01:39.080
school. And he taught the mathematics there. And 
this was back in time that the Depression was

01:42.140 --> 01:47.700
coming on us out there. And all he got out of that 
year's teaching at that little junior college was

01:53.470 --> 01:56.070
an Underwood typewriter, which I have at home. 
That was all they could pay. And I went to school. It

02:00.370 --> 02:02.450
was a little one-room school. It was a little 
schoolhouse. First grade in the first row, second

02:03.910 --> 02:05.970
grade in the second. Pot-bellied stove. Down at 
the bottom on old slick red hill was an outhouse.

02:11.490 --> 02:13.131
And all the kids went to the outhouse. And also the 
water was simply a barrel just like you'd see a keg

02:13.310 --> 02:17.790
of beer. And so Dad said, when we went there, I 
better put you back in the first grade because I

02:24.290 --> 02:26.950
don't want you to get behind. So I started out in the 
first. Well, in that school, you could get.

02:33.110 --> 02:33.554
Promoted. All you had to do was just show you could 
do the second grade work. So before the year was

02:37.450 --> 02:40.170
over, I was over in the second grade. Second row. 
They'd moved me to the second. So you just changed

02:42.450 --> 02:43.611
seats. You didn't know. No paperwork. Before the 
end of the year, I was in the third row. Well, then we

02:48.990 --> 02:53.810
moved to Stony Point, which is about 60 miles from 
Charlotte. And it's still very primitive in those

02:54.830 --> 02:59.670
days. But it did have a consolidated school. They 
bused all the kids from the county into that

03:02.730 --> 03:05.810
school. So Dad said, well, I know you were in the 
third grade there, but I think I'll put you back and

03:09.410 --> 03:12.290
let you do the second over. I don't want you to get 
behind. Well, they put me in that second grade, and

03:14.010 --> 03:16.470
I stayed the whole year because they didn't know 
how to get me out of it even though I knew it. Well,

03:19.770 --> 03:24.250
right after Christmas, we went back there and was 
looking for this. We wanted to go to all the places

03:24.230 --> 03:26.310
that we'd lived. And so we went to North 
Wilkesboro, and there was a bypass, and we stopped

03:30.650 --> 03:32.051
at a McDonald's. No. This Mountain View wasn't 
even on the map yet. And so we went there to stop at a

03:36.190 --> 03:39.350
McDonald's, and I saw a well-dressed lady over 
there. And I went over and struck up a conversation

03:41.710 --> 03:44.470
with her. And I asked her if she knew where Mountain 
View was. She said, oh, it's just right up here. You

03:49.470 --> 03:51.011
turn off right up the road here. Now, let me point 
out that in those years, Wilkes County was noted to

03:54.150 --> 04:00.290
be the biggest white lightning county in the 
United States. And so. She said, yes, I went to

04:03.663 --> 04:09.770
school there, one little one-room schoolhouse 
outhouse down at the bottom of the hill. And so then

04:09.750 --> 04:15.130
I went on back and sat down, and she came back over 
afterwards. And she told my daughter, or my

04:16.170 --> 04:21.830
sister, that her husband had passed away. And she 
says, well, what did he do? She says, oh, he was a

04:26.690 --> 04:28.151
bootlegger. Says that was the only way to make a 
living in those years. Didn't the law get after

04:32.230 --> 04:33.551
him? She said, oh, yes, he built time five 
different times. So this was kind of the area that I

04:37.410 --> 04:42.130
grew up in. And my dad and I, he was always gone a lot 
and so forth. And we just didn't have these

04:50.390 --> 04:55.910
father-to-son talks that you always have 
nowadays. You'll hear of, like Andy Hardy and

04:56.510 --> 04:59.310
Judge Stone. The closest we ever came to it was, the 
day we were packing the car, he was getting ready to

05:04.110 --> 05:07.090
take me off to this little Baptist Junior College, 
Mars Hill, out from Nashville, North Carolina.

05:10.370 --> 05:14.850
And it was always assumed that I'd go to college. It 
was never even, we just didn't discuss it. And I

05:17.790 --> 05:22.050
delivered papers there, and I knew all the 
professional people in town, and they said,

05:22.110 --> 05:25.530
you've got, there's a lot of emphasis there on you 
need to, you need to go to college and make

05:25.730 --> 05:28.110
something yourself. You heard that over and over 
again. And so, as we were packing the car, dad said

05:30.390 --> 05:34.970
to me, he says, son, what are you going to study when 
you get up there? I said, well, dad, I thought I'd

05:39.980 --> 05:42.100
study dentistry. He said, no, son, I don't think 
I'd do that if I were you. I don't believe you'll

05:45.340 --> 05:47.500
ever be able to keep up with your tools. Well, see, 
I'd lost his saw and hammer so many times that he was

05:48.260 --> 05:52.340
just, and he said, why don't you just go ahead and 
study engineering? Well, that's what I did. And

05:56.440 --> 06:00.920
so, after the pre-engineering course up there, 
Mars Hill, I went to North Carolina. And my junior

06:02.400 --> 06:05.900
year, I was having breakfast, and that's when 
Pearl Harbor hit. Actually, the day we were

06:08.380 --> 06:10.340
packing the car, the Germans marched in Europe, 
which marked the beginning, which is the day I

06:13.940 --> 06:15.501
started to college. And then when I was in my junior 
year at North Carolina State, the Germans, the

06:18.740 --> 06:21.440
Pearl Harbor occurred. So I went down, and I didn't 
want to get drafted. I wanted to finish school. So

06:26.800 --> 06:30.520
what I did was they had a program there where you 
could become, get a direct commission. Even

06:32.540 --> 06:35.900
though you hadn't been in ROTC, they had an ROTC 
there, and people marched around all the time. And

06:37.640 --> 06:40.620
they told me I wasn't in point in taking it because I 
could only do two years of it, so I didn't take it.

06:44.180 --> 06:47.600
But I went down and got a direct commission to go in 
the Navy. And so as soon as I finished college, I had

06:48.580 --> 06:51.120
to go in the Navy. And I was in the Navy and on 
destroyers for about, just nearly four years was

06:55.100 --> 06:57.600
the tour date. And the roughest duty that we had was 
on Okinawa. We went up there. We went up there with

07:02.300 --> 07:04.240
nine destroyers in the squadron. And this is where 
the kamikazes. And for about two or three months,

07:06.380 --> 07:11.100
we were exposed to kamikazes every day. And we lost 
six out of our nine destroyers. There were only

07:14.860 --> 07:17.460
three of us that made it back. And it was just a 
matter of luck. We weren't that much better. And we

07:21.400 --> 07:25.360
just, when they'd hit one station, we'd be on 
another one. Or the plane that was coming in at you,

07:25.460 --> 07:29.460
we got it shot down. Well, then after the war, I 
thought about going to Georgia Tech, but it turned

07:35.620 --> 07:37.720
out that there was no housing down there. So I 
decided I'd work for Burlington Mills. And they

07:40.420 --> 07:43.260
had put me into a little program that was supposed 
to be training the plant managers of the future.

07:46.780 --> 07:49.320
Well, it turned out that it looked like I was going 
to have to work on the third shift for about 10

07:49.300 --> 07:51.940
years, 15. So I decided I'd just go back to graduate 
school and went back to North Carolina State. And

07:57.140 --> 07:59.200
Dr. Lindsey had taught down there. And so they gave 
me his name. I called him. And got in touch with him.

08:04.440 --> 08:05.621
And so we came out here. And I began studying the 
graduate program in chemical engineering in

08:10.920 --> 08:13.580
January of 1948. That's it. You came to Texas A&M? 
Texas A&M in January 1948. And I promised my wife,

08:18.380 --> 08:20.840
because we'd been out here when I was on the 
destroyer, I promised her we'd never stay in

08:22.820 --> 08:24.640
Texas. As soon as I got my degree, we were leaving. 
Well, we stayed. Still here. Describe what was...

08:31.620 --> 08:33.700
what Texas A&M was physically. What was... Okay. 
What buildings... I'll give you the whole

08:35.235 --> 08:36.360
picture. I have some... A guy named Proctor was one 
of the first heads of the extension service, as I

08:43.300 --> 08:45.600
understand. And he was my brother-in-law's... my 
brother-in-law's mother's father. He used to be

08:55.640 --> 08:58.620
over here in this same place of research. He used to 
have a picture over there. So I... We visited with

09:00.760 --> 09:02.700
the... Mr. Lee's on the way. And Mr. Lee had been 
grad... had been taught... He'd been a high school

09:07.100 --> 09:08.561
principal. He'd gone to the old school and studied 
the Latin. He was a classical type individual. And

09:13.980 --> 09:14.821
he said... So he called up Bolton. Bolton was the 
executive vice president. Said, get this... get

09:18.860 --> 09:21.540
him a room, a place to stay up there. So after I'd 
already come here and gotten settled, I was over in

09:24.620 --> 09:26.640
Lindsey's office one day. And Mr. Bolton called up 
and he said he wanted to see me. Boy, they were just

09:30.060 --> 09:31.621
shaking over there. I went over. And... So he told 
me. But the amusing thing is... And then he ended up

09:36.180 --> 09:39.400
saying, well, just go over here and... Oh, I've 
forgotten... Boyette, go see him. He's in charge

09:42.940 --> 09:44.061
of housing. And that was what I got out of him. About 
a month or so, we were down there visiting with Mr.

09:47.680 --> 09:51.400
Lee again. He said... He said, well, I suppose you 
know Bolton well by now. I said, I'm sorry, Mr. Lee.

09:59.440 --> 10:02.580
Our paths haven't crossed any since that one time I 
met him. But Dr. Lindsey was head of the Chemical

10:03.000 --> 10:07.060
Engineering Department. We were over there in the 
old Petroleum Building. At that time, Barlow was

10:09.440 --> 10:13.620
Dean of Engineering. And

10:13.600 --> 10:19.410
Saul Wright was head of Civil. Charlie Crawford 
was head of Mechanical. Let's

10:22.590 --> 10:26.046
see. Shepard was Dean of Agriculture. Petroleum? 
No, Petroleum. Harold Vance was head of

10:31.160 --> 10:33.180
Petroleum. And Shepard was head of Agriculture. 
And I don't remember... I remember Mr. Porter was

10:37.860 --> 10:41.580
head of the Math Department. But I don't know... I 
don't remember now who was the Science Dean. I

10:45.440 --> 10:47.580
think Pearson was Dean of the Graduate College, 
followed later by Trotter. But Pearson, I

10:49.460 --> 10:51.720
believe, was the Dean when I came here. I worked 
most of the time, dealt with Trotter's group over

10:51.700 --> 10:54.940
there. And I think that's... Let's see. Street was 
teaching drawing. And I can't remember the

11:01.620 --> 11:03.540
fellow. It was head of Aero. And that's about the 
one. There were no sidewalks. It was all...

11:10.350 --> 11:13.050
Actually, it was the same way it was in 1943. They 
had done nothing during the war. And what I came in,

11:16.150 --> 11:20.330
we had already gotten over the flood here, but 
there's still a lot of veterans. And I would say

11:22.980 --> 11:27.020
that that was the toughest group to compete with 
I've ever ran against because all they want to know

11:27.000 --> 11:28.940
is what's required. And we'll do it. Because you 
and your other veteran buddies, you were

11:34.180 --> 11:38.040
mentally, emotionally mature. Ready to go to 
work. Ready to go to work. You'd had experience.

11:42.360 --> 11:44.020
And also, you could separate... I had a family, 
too. Everything was riding on it. What was your

11:46.900 --> 11:51.640
graduate student stipend or assistantship or 
what? Oh, it was probably about $100 a month. Plus

11:56.180 --> 11:57.701
the GI Bill. I'm not even sure we got $100. Maybe we 
did. I don't remember what it was. But it was living

12:01.980 --> 12:03.940
in College View. We could make it. But, see, by the 
time I got ready to finish, I ran out of the... I took

12:09.630 --> 12:11.191
a job teaching. I ran out of the GI Bill. So I had to 
take a job teaching. And then I had to buy a house

12:15.150 --> 12:18.830
over in College Hills. And I bought one on 
Harrington Street over there. It cost $13,700.

12:24.870 --> 12:30.290
And that was the poorest year that I've ever 
experienced in my life. My salary was $370. $370 a

12:34.250 --> 12:35.311
month. And Lindsey had to get special 
dispensation to get me $370. And so that's kind of

12:41.670 --> 12:46.090
what it was like here then. Now, when did you switch 
officially in paperwork from being a graduate

12:50.150 --> 12:53.050
student to being a faculty member? About 52. Okay. 
So you're... All right. We're still talking about

12:55.070 --> 12:57.010
the graduate student days. Yeah. Well, I 
finished... I got my PhD in 53, but I'd already...

13:00.830 --> 13:01.946
Oh, okay. I took a job as instructor. In 52, I think 
it was. And then I believe in... I guess in 53, that

13:11.590 --> 13:17.770
fall, I went ahead... I've forgotten whether I got 
promoted to assistant professor. Maybe I went a

13:20.770 --> 13:24.070
year before I got made assistant professor. 
Looking back now with the clear vision of

13:24.370 --> 13:29.010
hindsight, what courses and what teachers, 
instructors, were the most important to you?

13:38.050 --> 13:41.350
Well, actually, we had some things back then and 
there that are better than they are now. And that is

13:43.770 --> 13:47.290
that we took courses outside the department, a lot 
of them. And I took mathematics. I had Luther. I had

13:52.620 --> 13:53.501
Bayes. And then Dr. Klippel and I, years later, we 
worked on... I'd just go over with him and spend an

13:57.680 --> 13:59.920
hour a day every once in a while. Every week, we'd 
have a meeting and prove theorems and so on. And

14:05.120 --> 14:09.780
chemistry, Jensen and Dr. Watson. I worked under 
Murdoch, Phil Murdoch in chemical engineering,

14:13.680 --> 14:15.141
but Watson was one of them. Another one that I took 
course over there was POTS, organic chemistry.

14:22.141 --> 14:25.900
And Kenny Hancock was another one that I took a 
course under. I also took a physics course and Dr.

14:29.011 --> 14:30.000
Weeks taught it. And then after I finished my 
coursework, I went back and took another course in

14:32.700 --> 14:36.100
kinetic theory under Dr. Silvey. Which goes way 
back. And old Dr. Silvey, the first day, there were

14:39.140 --> 14:43.620
three of us in there registered for his course. And 
he, two physics students and me. And he said, he

14:49.360 --> 14:52.800
said, Mr. Tarlin, would you like to participate in 
the classroom discussion? And I said, well, I

14:57.140 --> 15:00.200
believe I'd like to do that. Well, what that 
amounted to, we were presenting one-third of that

15:00.180 --> 15:03.800
course for audit. Mm-hmm. And then I also had there 
one under Dr. Weeks over there. He was the first

15:11.780 --> 15:12.681
one. I took x-rays and crystallography, and I 
never had vectors. And he just, he had the course

15:15.660 --> 15:21.560
full of it, but I learned it, picked it up from him. 
And I had to compete against two graduate physics

15:21.540 --> 15:26.520
students in there, or three. And so Jensen was an 
outstanding chemistry teacher. Watson was an

15:33.070 --> 15:36.070
outstanding chemistry teacher. In fact, all of 
those people, Potts was never a real outstanding

15:38.050 --> 15:41.210
teacher. He had a tremendous amount of knowledge, 
but he could never finish one sentence until he

15:44.030 --> 15:47.370
started another one. Now, what was his first name? 
Because I remember Dr. Potts in agriculture. No,

15:52.510 --> 15:54.051
this was a different Potts. I don't remember what 
his first name is. You just have to look it up. What

15:56.350 --> 15:57.470
department? Chemistry. In the chemistry 
department? He was the organic prof in chemistry.

16:02.230 --> 16:04.970
Kenny Hancock taught a good course in chemistry. 
All right, what about within chemical

16:04.950 --> 16:07.910
engineering? Who were the key? Phil Murdock, I 
took a course under him, and

16:08.890 --> 16:15.690
let's see, you know that, I may have taken most all 
the courses I took under him. I took one under GL

16:19.050 --> 16:21.330
Fair. He taught process control, and I took that. 
But we took, in those years, we were really taking,

16:24.430 --> 16:29.730
see we didn't teach our own mathematics in our 
department, and now all these people trying to do,

16:29.710 --> 16:35.430
teach everything in one department, they never 
see the light of day outside the walls of their

16:35.410 --> 16:38.190
department. Did anybody, do you remember any 
advice that somebody gave you, which later proved

16:38.190 --> 16:43.830
to be very valuable advice to a chemical engineer? 
Oh, I don't know. I just kind of stumbled along, I

16:51.670 --> 16:55.730
guess. I very nearly quit shortly after, about 
1955, because I went down to Exxon, and that worked

17:03.170 --> 17:06.930
one summer, and they wanted me to stay with Exxon. 
And at that time, I was in the lab. I was in the lab. I

17:09.430 --> 17:16.300
was making $5,000 a year, Dr. Harris was making 
$5,100 a year, and Dr. Lindsey was making $5,200 a

17:16.280 --> 17:17.301
year. And I was an assistant professor, and both of 
them were full, and I figured, well, why should I

17:21.700 --> 17:28.900
stay here when that's all I've got, that's all the 
future I've got? So it was, Shirley Lynch,

17:28.880 --> 17:33.380
incidentally, in that old building, was head of 
geology over there, and that. What persuaded you

17:38.150 --> 17:40.220
to stay? Well, I just got to thinking about it that, 
I don't know.

17:48.380 --> 17:56.560
What had happened was, I had to hurry up and get 
through, because that one year, Phil Murdock left

17:56.540 --> 18:05.880
and Watson left, and all my committee left, so I 
really pushed that to get it completed.

18:05.860 --> 18:10.260
I wasn't really sure whether I wanted to stay, I 
guess, in that corporate structure. You don't

18:10.240 --> 18:13.880
have nears much freedom. What was your 
dissertation topic and your area of

18:13.860 --> 18:16.880
specialization? This was, I'd done my Masters on 
distillation, and this one was on catalytic,

18:16.860 --> 18:24.970
study of catalyst. And so on my committee I had Dr. 
Potts from biology, or Potter. Potter from

18:33.940 --> 18:36.520
biology. And Dr. Weeks, and Dr. Watson, and Phil 
Murdock. Yes, that's right. I believe were the

18:41.240 --> 18:48.140
ones on it and I couldn't get that arranged for the 
final meeting and I went by Watson's house one

18:48.720 --> 18:53.260
Afternoon late and he was sitting back in the 
backyard of the shirt off drinking beer And I told

18:53.480 --> 18:59.340
him I don't know that I'm gonna be able to graduate 
this time because I can't get this committee

18:53.480 --> 18:59.340
together Jordan says oh I can take care of that for 
you And he went in and called him up and we met over in

19:02.180 --> 19:08.020
the old patrolling building that night He set it up 
and we all met over there and I got it over with so I

19:08.000 --> 19:12.160
made it Do you remember any special questions on 
that? That final oral exam. I don't remember. I

19:18.652 --> 19:19.540
just remember that They asked me some question and 
I guess it's when you're working on some of those

19:20.580 --> 19:26.380
things you got so many Details in your mind. It's 
some little simple something You won't see And

19:32.380 --> 19:38.020
they asked me that and then they found the weakness 
and so they just I don't remember what it was but

19:38.620 --> 19:40.640
then they just One after another, you know, and 
that a part I remember if you know it Let's go on to

19:46.960 --> 19:51.780
the next, you know, but if you ever find something 
that you didn't know As you Thought about it then

19:53.460 --> 19:58.060
and now look back How did our chemical engineering 
department? How did our strength compare?

20:05.290 --> 20:07.570
nationally in the mid 50s Oh We were really a young 
department then we and in fact, we got down Because

20:14.870 --> 20:17.130
the salaries were so poor that at one time We were 
down to just Dr. Harry's Dr. Lindsay and I and we had

20:24.260 --> 20:28.080
to get some graduate students help us out So it's 
all we could do to keep keep the doors open. You're

20:30.718 --> 20:33.900
saying three faculty we got down to three faculty 
Everybody quit because salaries they went to

20:33.880 --> 20:37.200
industry or somewhere Because salaries were so 
poor back in those days and that's about when I was

20:37.180 --> 20:43.940
about ready to throw in the towel Was then when 
where the real change come was when John Connolly

20:44.620 --> 20:51.800
got in there salaries went up hours went up 30% a 
year For three or four years there, but now let's

20:52.660 --> 20:55.880
let's back up John Calhoun came here as Dean in the 
50s did Marlowe was head it was Dean when I came here

21:04.180 --> 21:06.700
Okay, and then John Calhoun came next All right Do 
you remember any early impressions of Calhoun as

21:06.680 --> 21:11.420
the Dean? I just remember that he was much more 
energetic than Well Barlow was energetic enough

21:20.020 --> 21:28.220
except that I thought about Calhoun was a much 
better individual and accountant and Barlow was

21:28.460 --> 21:33.893
What did Calhoun did he come over and visit did he 
become acquainted with y'all? Oh, yeah, he had us

21:33.914 --> 21:34.980
over He had me over to his office And I think he was 
kind of leery of old dr. Lindsay and Doc had already

21:40.860 --> 21:45.600
told him Calhoun told me he says right here's my 
Territory no, there's your don't you get in here?

21:49.340 --> 21:52.920
Don't you come across it, but he did ask me one time 
He had me in his office talking. I think I irritated

21:55.555 --> 21:59.040
him because he said to me he said Wait, you're 
saying he is this Calhoun. That's Calhoun. Okay.

22:03.452 --> 22:04.440
He won't know of any Any a the dis Incentives or 
negative things about Lindsay. Mm-hmm. I said

22:12.565 --> 22:15.420
well even if I had some I wouldn't tell you So that 
ended that discussion I may have heard his feeling

22:16.220 --> 22:22.320
but because I was pretty loyal to the old doc Was did 
the best he could with what he had and he didn't have

22:22.300 --> 22:26.340
much to work with Now the enrollment I'm assuming 
in engineering in the 50s was going up. Well, no

22:31.843 --> 22:35.640
actually what happened was enrollment of 
everybody's went down to about 1955 was a low

22:35.620 --> 22:37.894
point. Oh, okay. I was after the war is over and this 
is about in there somewhere Maybe even after that

22:42.320 --> 22:47.160
they decided that they wanted to make it optional 
core a little bit And I think we went on that program

